english:
  title: Preface to a Poetry Collection Presented to Yu Sa-am
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The gentleman possesses a joy that endures throughout life. The fleeting pleasures of a single day cannot constitute true joy. When there is no favoritism, no rejection—when in movement and stillness, in looking up and bowing down, not even a trace of shame takes root—then that which we call the self remains serene and intact within. Life and death, longevity and brevity: these come from Heaven. Fortune and misfortune, honor and disgrace: these come from man. Yet none of these are truly ourselves. When we mistake them for reasons to rejoice or fear, emotion has overcome our nature. When emotion dominates and does not cease, the Way of Heaven begins to fade. To claim in such a state that one possesses lifelong joy—I cannot believe this.

    Office ennobles us, salary enriches us. Yet he who can enrich may also impoverish; he who can ennoble may also degrade. We dare not resist these commands precisely because the authority rests with another, not with ourselves. Thus what was never truly ours may suddenly be bestowed upon us. Though we achieve the ultimate in wealth and station, we cannot rejoice in it—for even rejoicing would be improper. How then could this become a lasting joy? True joy, one must discover for oneself. A father cannot transfer his joy to his son; a husband cannot steal it from his wife. Between the closest of all relations—parent and child, husband and wife—such things cannot be passed or taken. There must be a reason for this. One who not merely understands this but practices it will find that external sorrows naturally cease.

    Master Yu Sa-am approaches this understanding. In the capital for eleven years, his colleagues recognized his noble conduct. Through fourteen years in government service, his fellow officials bowed to his magnanimous spirit. Rising from common cloth to the seat of prime minister—truly a pinnacle. Yet not a trace of self-satisfaction appears in his words or bearing. Observe his dwelling, his clothing, his food, those with whom he associates—all the trappings of wealth and station—yet his face remains as it was in his humble days. Does he not refuse to make a single day's pleasure into lasting joy? Among those who tower and gleam for decades, few maintain their integrity to the end. Master Yu moves through advancement and retreat with composure, seeing no honor in office nor shame in retirement. Once in the halls of power, he found joy in seeing the Way take root; now in the countryside, he finds joy in preserving his wholeness. The self intact, the Way intact as well. The days of old dissolve like drifting clouds, leaving no trace, yet his devoted heart toward his sovereign remains inseparable from his enduring joy. Should this ever be severed, could it still be what I call true joy?

    Kang Ja-ya, Keeper of Rites at the National Academy, is Master Yu's student. He seeks to gather poems from worthy men as sustenance for his retreat, and having requested that I, who know the Master well, write this preface, I have briefly set down these essentials. Did not Zhuangzi say: 'One who dwells in emptiness, hearing merely the sound of human footsteps, suddenly knows joy'? How much more so with these words. The reader will surely tap his knee and sigh: 'How essential it is that kindred spirits exist in this world!'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Sa-am (思菴) refers to Yu Gyeong, a prominent Goryeo official known for his moral integrity and graceful transitions between public service and private life.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Zhuangzi appears near the end, drawing on Daoist philosophy to emphasize the spiritual recognition between kindred souls.
  - key: ''
    value: The preface itself is an illustration of the principle it advocates—Lee Saek's genuine appreciation of Yu's character transcends worldly concerns of rank and fortune.
